''[[The Hurt Locker]]'' is a 2008 [[Iraq War]] film written by [[Mark Boal]] and directed by [[Kathryn Bigelow]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2008/sep/08/entertainment/et-hurt8|title=The Iraq war -- from the troops' point of view  - Los Angeles Times|last=Mark|first=Olsen|date=September 8, 2008|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|accessdate=May 20, 2010}}</ref> The film premiered on September 4, 2008 at the [[65th Venice International Film Festival]], where it competed with ''[[The Wrestler (2008 film)|The Wrestler]]'' for the [[Golden Lion]] award. It was released in Italy by [[Warner Bros. Pictures]] on October 10, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.variety.com/index.asp?layout=festivals&jump=story&id=1061&articleid=VR1117991591&cs=1|title='Hurt Locker' gives Venice a Jolt|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Reed Business Information]]|first=Nick|last=Vivarelli|date=September 4, 2008|accessdate=May 1, 2010}}</ref> Following a showing at the [[2008 Toronto International Film Festival|33rd Toronto International Film Festival]], [[Summit Entertainment]] picked the film up for distribution in the United States.<ref name="Defies">{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/aug/06/entertainment/et-word6|title=The Hurt Locker Defies the Odds|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|first=John|last=Horn|date=August 6, 2009|accessdate=May 1, 2010}}</ref> ''The Hurt Locker'' was released in the United States on June 26, 2009, with a limited release at four theaters in [[Los Angeles]] and [[New York City]].<ref>{{cite web|last=McClintock|first=Pamela|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118005300.html?categoryid=1082&cs=1|title='Transformers' expected to crash B.O.|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Reed Business Information]]|date=June 23, 2009|accessdate=May 4, 2009}}</ref> The film grossed over $145,000 on its opening weekend, averaging around $36,000 per theater. The following weekend, beginning July 3, the film grossed over $131,000 at nine theaters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=weekend&id=hurtlocker.htm|title=The Hurt Locker (2009) â Weekend Box Office Results| work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|publisher=[[IMDb]]|accessdate=June 22, 2010}}</ref> It held the highest per-screen average{{#tag:ref|The per-screen average is the box office gross for the weekend, divided by the number of screens nationwide that the film was shown on that weekend.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://johnaugust.com/archives/2009/per-screen-average|title=Per-screen average|last=August|first=John|date=June 30, 2009|publisher=johnaugust.com|accessdate=May 29, 2010}}</ref> |group=Note}} of any movie playing theatrically in the United States for the first two weeks of its release, gradually moving into the top 20 chart.<ref name="bom">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=hurtlocker.htm|title=The Hurt Locker (2009)|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|publisher=[[IMDb]]|accessdate=May 4, 2010 }}</ref><ref name="APTop20">{{cite web |url=http://www.accesshollywood.com/500-days-of-summer/harry-potter-franchise-shows-no-sign-of-slowing_article_20799 |title='Harry Potter' franchise shows no sign of slowing|date=July 20, 2009|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|accessdate=May 4, 2010}}</ref> Summit Entertainment then released ''The Hurt Locker'' to more screens. {{As of|May 2010}}, the film has grossed over $40&nbsp;million worldwide.<ref name="bom" />

''The Hurt Locker'' has earned various awards and nominations, with the nominations in categories ranging from recognition of the screenplay to its direction and editing to the cast's acting performance. Kathryn Bigelow dominated the Best Director category at the critics' circles. The [[67th Golden Globe Awards]] ceremony saw ''The Hurt Locker'' receive three nominations for Best Motion Picture Drama, Director and Screenplay, but it failed to win any. The film garnered nine nominations at the [[82nd Academy Awards]]; the ceremony saw the film come away with six awards, including Best Motion Picture, Director and Original Screenplay. Bigelow became the first woman to win the Academy Award for Best Director and she also became only the fourth woman to be nominated in the category in the history of the awards.<ref name="BigelowOscar">{{cite news|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/2010/mar/08/kathryn-bigelow-oscars-best-director|title=Kathryn Bigelow makes history as first woman to win best director Oscar|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=[[Guardian News and Media Limited]]|first=Matthew|last=Weaver|date=March 8, 2010|accessdate=May 20, 2010}}</ref> 

''The Hurt Locker'' received two nominations at the [[16th Screen Actors Guild Awards]], for Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor for [[Jeremy Renner]] and Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture. The film won the Best Theatrical Motion Picture and Outstanding Directorial Achievement at the [[Producers Guild of America Awards 2009|21st Producers Guild of America Awards]] and the 62nd Directors Guild of America Awards respectively. The [[Los Angeles Film Critics Association Awards 2009|35th LA Film Critics Association Awards]], [[2009 New York Film Critics Circle Awards|75th NY Film Critics Circle Awards]] and the [[National Society of Film Critics Awards 2009|44th National Society of Film Critics Association Awards]] saw the film win awards for Best Picture and Director. Both the [[American Film Institute]] and the [[Associated Press]] included ''The Hurt Locker'' in their Top Ten Films of 2009 lists.<ref name="AFIBest">{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/dec/14/entertainment/la-et-critics14-2009dec14|title=Prize-filled day for 'The Hurt Locker'|last=King|first=Susan|date=December 14, 2009|work=Los Angeles Times|publisher=Tribune Company|accessdate=April 30, 2010}}</ref><ref name="AP2009">{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/wireStory?id=9316068|title=AP Critics Germain, Lemire Pick Top Films of 2009|last=Germain|first=David|coauthors=Christy Lemire|date=December 11, 2009|work=ABC News|publisher=American Broadcasting Company|accessdate=April 30, 2010}}</ref> The Associated Press also placed the film at number six on their Top Ten Films of the Decade list.<ref name="APBest">{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/wireStory?id=9315304|title=AP Critics Germain, Lemire Pick Decade's Top Films|last=Germain|first=David|coauthors=Christy Lemire|date=December 11, 2009|work=ABC News|publisher=American Broadcasting Company|accessdate=April 30, 2010}}</ref>

